    <!-- Info Screen -->
    <string name="info_title_history">History of the Pips</string>
    <string name="info_text_history">The \"pips\" are a series of short audio tones broadcast by radio stations to mark the precise start of an hour. The most famous is the Greenwich Time Signal (GTS), first broadcast by the BBC in 1924. They were originally created to allow the public and ship navigators to calibrate their clocks and chronometers accurately.</string>

    <string name="info_title_technical">Technical Motivations</string>
    <string name="info_text_technical">Before digital networks, transmitting exact time over long distances was challenging. Radio provided a near-instantaneous medium. The classic BBC signal consists of five short 1kHz tones (0.1 seconds long) followed by a final, longer tone (0.5 seconds). The actual start of the exact hour coincides with the very beginning of that final, long pip.</string>

    <string name="info_title_composition">How to compose Pips</string>
    <string name="info_text_composition">This application allows you to recreate classic time signals or invent your own.\n\n• Each Pip has 8 available slots.\n• Set a Frequency (Hz) for the tone pitch. Use 0 Hz to create a silent pause.\n• Set a Duration (ms) for how long the tone or silence lasts.\n• The audio engine plays the slots sequentially. Empty slots (0 Hz and 0 ms) are automatically skipped.</string>
    <string name="info_title_how_it_works">How it works</string>
    <string name="info_text_how_it_works">1. Library: Create and test your custom Pips.\n2. Schedule: Set up the rules (days, hours, and minutes) for when your Pips should play.\n3. Master Switch: To save battery, the app remains completely asleep by default. You must turn the Master Switch ON (available on the Schedule screen).\n\nFor your convenience, you can also add \'The Pips\' Quick Settings Tile in your Android notification dropdown to easily toggle it ON and OFF.</string>

